Ford GoBike System Dataset Exploration and Visualization¶

Created by Alex Yu

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The bicycle-sharing service is becoming more and more popular across the globe. It allows people in metropolitan areas to rent bicycles by unlocking in one station and return in any other authorized network station. This is very convenient for short trips, especially ideal for one-way trips.

Ford GoBike, which was initiated in 2013, is one of them that was introduced to the US West Coast. Up until now, it has facilitated hundreds of thousands of people and collected millions of usage data since 2017.

Data Gathering¶

In the following step, firstly we make a list of filenames in order to download data from s2.amazonaws.com; secondly we use requests library to parse the url and download data accordingly; thirdly as the downloaded files are in zip format, we need to unzip these files to their csv format. After being unzipped, the zip files are deleted.

Notice: The data sets are stored here.

In [ ]:
# Create urls list for requesting data from aws s3
url_prefix = "https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/"
url_fliter = list(range(201801, 201813)) + list(range(201901, 201905))

urls = []
for i in url_fliter:
    url = url_prefix + str(i) + "-fordgobike-tripdata.csv.zip"
    urls.append(url)
    
urls.append('https://s3.amazonaws.com/fordgobike-data/2017-fordgobike-tripdata.csv')

In [ ]:
# Request and download data from aws s3
for url in urls:
    response = requests.get(url)
    with open(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'data', url.split('/')[-1]), 'wb') as infile:
        infile.write(response.content)
In [ ]:
# Unzip all the downloaded `.zip` files into its `.csv` format and delete the original `.zip`
for file in glob.glob(os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'data/*.zip')):
    with zipfile.ZipFile(file, mode='r') as myFile:
        myFile.extractall(path=os.path.join(os.getcwd(), 'data'))
        os.remove(file)

        print(idx, col_name)

def concat_csvs(filenames):
    """Concatenate multiple csv format data based on file names."""
    
    # Store the read-in DataFrame in a list
    dfs = []
    
    # Iterate filenames list and read data into pandas DataFrame
    for filename in filenames:
        df = pd.read_csv(filename, low_memory=False)
        dfs.append(df)
    
    return pd.concat(dfs, ignore_index=True)

Summary - Data Type Check:

As shown from above, I find several inappropriate data types in the dataset as follows,

  • start_time, end_time could be timestamps data type instead of object (string).
  • start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id could be object (string) instead of float64.
  • member_birth_year could be int instead of float64.
  • member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip could be CategoricalDtype instead of object (string).

Summary - Missingness Check:

The visualized missingness is similar to the statistical summary we got previously. Interestingly we can see that the missingness in member_birth_year and member_gender seems to happen at the same time which means that if the record in member_birth_year is absent, the record in member_gender of the same row is also absent. So ignoring them won't have much impact on the information the original dataset holds. (If the missingness in these two columns happens in different records (rows), we may lose more data or information.) As for the bike_share_for_all_trip which is a programme initiated since 2018, the missingness in the year of 2017 is intuitive.

Now we can answer the following questions based on the analysis from above.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

I retrieved the data from Ford GoBike's AWS S3 Storage which includes 1 .csv file and 16 .zip file.

After combining these files, I found that it has 3,254,325 records covering 23 months of usage data ranging between June 2017 and April 2019, although data in 2017 has 15 features without bike_share_for_all_trip column, the rest are exactly the same.

16 features includes:

  • duration_sec
  • start_time
  • end_time
  • start_station_id
  • start_station_name
  • start_station_latitude
  • start_station_longitude
  • end_station_id
  • end_station_name
  • end_station_latitude
  • end_station_longitude
  • bike_id
  • user_type
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The ultimate goal of the project is to analyze what kinds of people are using the Ford GoBike service in the SF Bay Area and how they are using it. As we can see from the 16 features listed above, I think the main feature of interest is duration_sec as it is directly correlated with the profits of the service and can help answer the question 'How are they using it?'. As per the question 'What kinds of people are using the service?', I find helpful features such as user_type, member_birth_year, bike_share_for_all_trip. Namely,

What kinds of people are using the Ford GoBike Service?

  • user_type
  • member_birth_year
  • member_gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip

How are they using it?

  • duration_sec
  • trip_distance_km

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Besides the raw featrues listed above in the dataset, I think it would be worthwhile to derive some other features such as member_age, year, month, date, day_of_week, hour etc. based on the original column member_birth_year and start_time or end_time because they would allow us to dive deeper into how these factors interact with or affect the duration_sec in finer granularity. Moreover, these derived ones would be more intuitive and interpretable to communicate the analytical results to the public compared with the raw features.

For the convenience of data cleaning, I conclude once again the data quality analysis result from above as belowjust at the head of Data Cleaning Part.

Quality Issues¶

  1. Columns have missing values
    • start_station_id - nullity: 0.38%,
    • start_station_name - nullity: 0.38%,
    • end_station_id - nullity: 0.38%,
    • end_station_name - nullity: 0.38%,
    • member_birth_year - nullity: 6.7%,
    • member_gender - nullity: 6.7%,
    • bike_share_for_all_trip - nullity: 15.97%.
  1. member_birth_year could be int instead of float64.
  1. member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip could be CategoricalDtype instead of object (string).
  1. start_station_id, end_station_id, bike_id could be object (string) instead of float64 or int.
  1. start_time, end_time could be timestamps data type instead of object (string).
  1. Some new features need to be derived:
    • member_age from member_birth_year
    • start_month from start_time
    • start_date from start_time
    • start_day_of_week from start_time (See Remark 1.)
    • start_hour from start_time
    • trip_distance from start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, end_station_longitude ((See Remark 2.))

Remark 1: After start_day_of_week is created, we can order them in real world by using pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype. Remark 2: This can be achieved by using distance() function from geopy.distance package.

  1. Abnormal value in member_birth_year with 1878.

Insights for Distribution of Duration Time

From the histogram on the left, we can see that the duration time is a right-skewed distribution. If we put it on a log-scale, see on the right, we can get an almost perfect normal distribution.

  • Half of the duration time for a ride fall bewteen 5.75 mins (Q1) and 13.9 mins (Q3) with average value being 12.9 mins.
  • 95% of the data fall within 27.3 minuets and 99% of the data fall within 63.95 minutes.
  • Extreme values can go up to as large as 1438 minutes (< 1%).
  • The distribution pattern seems to be aligned with the policy saying Membership includes the first 45 minutes of each trip for free; Rides longer than 45 minutes are $2 for each additional 15 minutes. It seems to reveals that each user is really an economic man.

Univariate Exploration 4. How are users with different genders distributed?¶

I defined a function to draw veritical bar plots for studying the distribution behavior of features like user_gender, user_type and bike_share_for_all_trip because the whole process from this on is quite similar to each other as well as following the DIY or Don't Repeat Yourself Principle.

In [72]:
def vertical_bar_plots(col, \
                       x_label, \
                       title_, \
                       y_min, \
                       y_max, \
                       interval, \
                       y_label='Number of Bike Rentals', \
                       pct_text_alignment=50_000, \
                       y_tick_unit='M'):
    
    """Plot bar charts with relative percentage annotation on categorical data"""
    
    # Calculate counts for each component under a categorical feature
    each_counts = master_clean[col].value_counts(sort=False)
    
    # Make count plot based on the categorical feature
    sns.countplot(data=master_clean, x=col, color=base_color)
    
    # Add dashed line for reading data easily in the plot
    plt.grid(axis='y', linestyle='--', alpha=.3)
    
    # Add relative frequency text for each
    total_counts = master_clean.shape[0]

    for i in range (each_counts.shape[0]):
        counts = each_counts[i]
        pct_string = '{:.2f}%'.format(100*counts/total_counts)
        plt.text(i, counts+pct_text_alignment, pct_string, ha='center')

    # Change unit representation on y ticks
    if y_tick_unit == 'M':
        # Change y tick scale from 1,000,000 to 1M 
        orig_ticks = np.arange(y_min, y_max, interval)
        new_ticks = ["{}M".format(i/1000000) for i in orig_ticks]
        plt.yticks(orig_ticks, new_ticks)
        
    elif y_tick_unit == 'K':
        # Change y tick scale from 1,000 to 1K
        orig_ticks = np.arange(y_min, y_max, interval)
        new_ticks = ["{}K".format(int(i/1000)) for i in orig_ticks]
        plt.yticks(orig_ticks, new_ticks)

    # Add label for x and y axis 
    plt.xlabel(x_label)
    plt.ylabel(y_label)

    # Add title
    plt.title(title_, fontdict={'fontsize':13}, pad=10);

  • As we can see, the general trend for the bike rentals is increasing over the years. At the beginning of 2017-06, there are only 2 thousand, however in 23 months, the total number mounts up to 220 thousand, almost 100 times larger.
  • Although the trend is increasing, it is not strictly linear but several obvious ups and downs. Interestingly, it seems all the sharp increases concentrate in the first half of a year. The peaks arrive at around October of the year. After that, it begins to decline. So there seems to be a seasonal reason for this as winter comes in and temperature is low, people tend not to choose bike as their transporation tool. But in pleasing climate like spring and summer with cozy weather conditions and sufficient sunlights, people tend to rent bicycle as a way to get close to nature.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  1. duration_min, which is derived from the original duration_sec, is one of the variables of my interest. After calculating its percentiles, I found out that, 99% of the data fall within 63.95 minutes, approximately 1 hour, while the maximum values goes up to 1438 minutes, about 24 hours which is unbelievable, so for studying the distribution pattern for most of the data, I filtered out those duration_min larger than 64 minutes which covers less than 1% of the whole data. Furthermore, when the duration_min was initially plotted using histogram, it presented a very long right tail. So I performed log scale on it and afterwards it presented approximately a normal distribution.

  2. As for the trip_distance_km, it also presented a normal distribution when applied log scale. Although there is a seemingly-like outlier, e.g. 64km, as what I analyzed in the data wranging process, I decided to keep it.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

In the data wrangling process, I performed several outlier detection process and found out that the member_age feature did have some unusual values (see age anomaly). The maximum age can be as large as 141 y/o while 99% of age values lie before the age of 66, so I filtered out those data whose ages are beyond 66 y/o.

I also filtered out data whose trip_distance_km is larger than 100 km (_see distance anomaly in the data wrangling process_) as the values larger than 100km can be as large as 10,000km which are obviously impossible for a bicycle ride in just less than 1 hour.

  • In the plot(0, 0), for males the average duration time in each month is relatively stable thoughout the year; For females the average duration in the first half of a year is slightly larger and more fluctuated than that in the second half of a year. Compared with the average distance for a ride in the plot(1, 0), all three curves seem to decrease gradually as month varies.
  • In the plot(0, 1), the curves follow very similar trend for all three types of gender, that is, on weekdays, average duration time is shorter tha that at the weekends. Further more, the average values for Female and Other are almost the same. In terms of average distance for rides (See the plot(1, 1)), all three curves present similar trend as well, that is, on weekdays, the values are larger than that at the weekends. Further more, the average values for Female and Other** are quite close to each other.
  • In the plot(0, 2), the other gender curve is more fluctuated. But the three curves all seem to have two lower valleys which are 5:00 - 9:00 in the morning and 16:00 - 19:00 in the evening. While in plot(1, 2), the trend is just the opposite to the average duration time curves: two humps happen around 8:00 in the morning and 17:00 in the evening. Interestingly, it seems during these periods, users tend to spend the least time to make the longest distance.

def draw_heatmap(*args, **kwargs):
    """Construct the dataframe and create heatmap."""
    data = kwargs.pop('data')
    d = data.pivot(index=args[0], columns=args[1], values=args[2])
    sns.heatmap(d, **kwargs)

# Instantiate a `FacetGrid` object
fg = sns.FacetGrid(type_df, col='user_type', height=8, aspect=.9, gridspec_kws={"wspace":0.1})

# Map heatmap object with `FacetGrid` object
fg.map_dataframe(draw_heatmap, \
                 'start_time_hour', \
                 'start_time_dow', \
                 'bike_id', \
                 cmap='flare', \
                 cbar=True, \
                 cbar_kws={"orientation": "horizontal", 'label':'Abs. Freq.'})

# Reset x and y labels
fg.axes[0,0].set_xlabel('Day in a Week')
fg.axes[0,1].set_xlabel('Day in a Week')
fg.axes[0,0].set_ylabel('Hour in a Day')
fg.axes[0,1].set_ylabel('Hour in a Day')

fg.fig.suptitle("Comparison of Bike Rentals in Day Of a Week and Hour of a Day by User Type" ,
               fontsize = 'x-large' , 
               fontweight = 'bold' );

Insights¶

From the heatmaps, we can clearly see some interesting patterns for the bicycle rental behaviors for different user types although the counts of rentals for Subscribers are as 10 times large as that for Customers:

  • From Monday to Friday, the rentals mostly happen during commute hours which are 7:00 - 9:00 in the morning and 16:00 - 18:00 in the afternoon, no matter what kind of user type they belong to.
  • On Saturday and Sunday, the difference between these two user types occurs: Customer users tend to rent bikes during weekends more often than they do on weekdays, especially during the period from 10:00 in the morning to 16:00 in the afternoon. However, Subscriber users seem to have disappeared during that period at the weekends, maybe they prefer taking a tour without bicycles or just relaxing at home.

Insights¶

  • For Customer user type, the average duration time distribution for different age ranges throughout days of a week mostly look like letter V shape on the point plots although there are a few exceptions. Generally, younger and older users are prone to spend longer average time for a ride, while users between 20 and 50 spend less.
  • For Customer user type, the confidence interval at the two ends of age ranges is wider than the others as those samples are very small.
  • For Subscriber user type, the average duration time distribution for different age ranges throughout days of a week are more stable: Subscriber users at younger age spend less average duration time for a ride, and as their ages grow, they tend to spend longer.
  • For Subscriber user type, the distribution pattern from Monday to Friday is quite similar which implies that they almost spend the same duration time for a ride every weekday.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • Males tend to spend less time and ran less distance for a ride, no matter we downscaled from time-based aspect or age-based aspect or user-type-based aspect.

From time-based aspect, no matter in the scale of months in a year, days in a week, or hours in a day (see Multi-variate Exploration 3), it is quite clear that Male curves are mostly below the other two types of gender.

From age-based aspect (see Multi-variate Exploration 9), it also shows that the general position of points for Males are lower than the other two types of gender.

From user-type-based aspect (see Multi-variate Exploration 5 and 6), the average duration time and distance in Male Customer or Male Subscriber, are the lowest among the three types of gender, no matter which user type they are.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

One of the biggest surprising interactions is the duration time v.s. days in a week when taking age into consideration. I have thought the 60+ people would be the ones who spent the longest duration time and ran the shortest distance per ride because they are less active and living more cautisouly than the youngers. But the result is it's the 10 - 20 y/o group, no matter it's scaled with other categorical features like gender or user type (refer to Multi-variate Exploration 8 and 9). Moreover, the average values for the 10 - 20 y/o group generally differ a lot or more dispersedly distributed and act like outliers from the others.
